  "prompt": "Do Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ use cumulative acknowledgements or an acknowledgement for every individual packet?",
  "response": "Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ differ in their use of acknowledgements:\n\n1. **Go-Back-N ARQ**:\n   - Uses **cumulative acknowledgements**.\n   - The receiver sends an acknowledgement (ACK) for the last correctly received in-order packet.\n   - If a packet is lost or arrives out of order, the receiver discards all subsequent packets and does not send individual ACKs for them.\n   - The sender retransmits all packets starting from the lost or corrupted packet when it detects a missing ACK (through a timeout or duplicate ACKs).\n\n2. **Selective Repeat ARQ**:\n   - Uses **individual acknowledgements** for every correctly received packet, whether in order or not.\n   - The receiver acknowledges each packet individually, even if they arrive out of order.\n   - The sender only retransmits the specific packets that are lost or corrupted, rather than retransmitting all subsequent packets.\n\nIn summary:\n- **Go-Back-N ARQ** uses **cumulative acknowledgements**.\n- **Selective Repeat ARQ** uses **individual acknowledgements**.",
